The Centre for Health Sciences Training, Research and Development (CHESTRAD) has recommended eight priority areas the country should focus on in the next three years as part of its post COVID-19 pandemic recovery strategy. It advised that “equity, inclusion, and solidarity” should be prioritised with focus on primary health care (PHC) through expansion of partnerships; particularly with the private sector to expand resource base for growth and sustainability. CHESTRAD’s strategic plan hopes to consolidate partnerships with a wide range of stakeholders including citizens and duty bearers to demand and entrench equitable access to health delivery and effective response to public health emergencies in the global south.   Buhari mourns The Guardian Editor-in-Chief’s dad     PDP stakeholders in 24 states have endorsed Atiku, says…     Kumuyi defends choice of speakers at youth programme   CHESTRAD Global President Dr. Lola Dare unveiled the plan in a statement. She explained that drawing on the huge lessons of the COVID-19 pandemic in terms of poor access to healthcare and economic disruptions with attendant impacts of the social media on citizens, policy and public trust as a result of infodemic, CHESTRAD has repositioned for short and long term strategies relevant in “identifying fit-for-purpose dynamic interventions at global, regional, and country (including sub-national levels) and across four iterative phases of a pandemic viz: rescue, recover, restore and reimagine”. - Advertisement - She added that within the strategic framework (2022 -2025), CHESTRAD would forge partnerships for multi-sector interventions with focus on: expanding access to financial services for women and young persons as a key component of COVID-19 bounce back investments and financial risk protection to achieve health SDGs.